  "body_html": "<div class=\"captioned-image-container\"><figure><a class=\"image-link image2\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png\" data-component-name=\"Image2ToDOM\"><div class=\"image2-inset\"><picture><source type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\"><img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png\" width=\"491\" height=\"229\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:229,&quot;width&quot;:491,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:288688,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:&quot;https://chillphysicsenjoyer.substack.com/i/171831034?img=https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:null,&quot;offset&quot;:false}\" class=\"sizing-normal\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v5ul!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F870a0c06-2d25-467b-9af7-c7f1382458e5_491x229.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\" fetchpriority=\"high\"></picture><div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>There are few people who manage wide, deep and meaningful friendship circles with ease. From my observations, there seems to be one common trait that connects them all. </p><p>They are <em>genuinely curious about lots of things</em>. </p><p>One of my best friends seems to know <em>everyone</em> in my home country. If I were to describe a core trait, it would be his relentless desire to learn anything out of pure interest - whether it\u2019s constitutional law, math, Abrahamic religions or financial derivatives. </p><p>The same goes for the most socially successful professionals and entrepreneurs I have met over time. One, who runs a bio company, always asks me interesting questions and lets people talk when we\u2019re in gatherings. </p><p>So why does <em>genuine curiosity</em> correlate with making friends? </p><p>Well, people love being cared about. And they are more likely to form deep relationships with those that care about them. And when someone asks you with <em>genuineness</em> about what you\u2019re thinking about, or how you\u2019re doing, it\u2019s hard to think of better ways to signal care.</p><p>But you can\u2019t force this. </p><p>Genuineness is hard to fake. So when someone is genuinely curious about things, they\u2019re more likely to ask people questions that really <em>hit the spot. </em>Questions that make them feel heard. </p><p>But if you can\u2019t fake genuineness, can you fake curiosity? </p><p>Probably not. But I think you can train it. Picking up a book and seeing what you enjoy. Trying to ask people more questions. Your social circle will either stay the same, or one might be positively surprised!</p>",
  "truncated_body_text": "There are few people who manage wide, deep and meaningful friendship circles with ease. From my observations, there seems to be one common trait that connects them all.",
